<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="334fe452-469d-51bf-8d5d-ee84409fe4cc" activityNameId="9e1f330c-fc25-499f-8b16-04e9aead76e5" parentActivityId="f963ada0-6743-486c-a4df-f8622b8c121c" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1" energyValues="0">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">alpha-naphthol production</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">C10H8O</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">Production of alpha-naphtol including materials, energy uses, infrastructure and emissions.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The process "alpha-naphtol, at plant, RER" is modelled for the production of alpha-naphtol  from naphtalene sulfonic acid in Europe. Raw materials are modelled with a stoechiometric calculation. Emissions are estimated.  Energy consumptions,  infrastructure and transports are calculated with standard values.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">α-Naphthol (C10H8O; CAS 90-15-3, 1-naphthol, 1-naphthalenol, 1-hydroxynaphthalene) forms colourless prisms (from toluene) which darken on exposure to air or light. The compound is steam volatile and sublimable.  α-Naphthol can be produced via caustic fusion of naphthalene-1-sulfonic acid, by hydrolysis of 1-naphthylamine  with aqueous 22 % sulfuric acid at 200 °C under pressure in a lead-lined autoclave, or by catalytic oxidation of tetralin to 1-tetralol and 1-tetralone followed by dehydrogenation. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">In this study caustic fusion of naphthalene sulfonic acid is considered:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">C10H8O3S + 2 NaOH → C10H8O + Na2SO4 + H2O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Several important agrochemicals are derived from α-naphthol.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">1-Naphthoxyacetic acid is prepared by aqueous alkylation with chloroacetic acid. Devrinol, Stauffer's 2-(1-naphthoxy)-N,N-diethylpropionamide herbicide, is obtained by the reaction of 1-naphthol and N,N-diethyl-α-bromopropionamide in MeOH – NaOMe at reflux. Sevin is Union Carbide's insecticide based on 1-naphthyl methylcarbamate, carbaryl, which is produced from 1-naphthyl chloroformate and methylamine or by reaction of 1-naphthol with methyl isocyanate. Its main use lies in the control of earthworms and certain caterpillars. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Important drugs are also derived from α-naphthol. The ester 1-naphthyl salicylate, Alphol, has been used as an antiseptic and antirheumatic, and ICI's 1-isopropylamino-3-(1-naphthoxy)-2-propanol, Inderal, is an important member of a new class of adrenergic β-blockers for the treatment of heart disease. Production of 21 involves reaction of 15 with epichlorohydrin followed by isopropylamine.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Related products used as β-blockers or antiarrhythmics include nadoxolol and nadolol. Many analogues and alternative syntheses of this type of compound have been patented.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">Condensation of 1-naphthol with aniline at 180 °C gives N-phenyl-1-naphthylamine which is used as a rubber antioxidant.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10">α-Naphthol is much less important than 2-naphthol as a dye intermediate. Apart from the historical interest in simple azo derivatives such as Orange I, the equilibrium with the keto form is an example of the prevalence of keto forms in many azo naphthol derivatives.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="11">Certain diazo components, for example, 1-amino-2-hydroxynaphthalene - 4 - sulfonic acid, under strongly alkaline conditions, couple with 1-naphthol in the 2-position rather than the conventional 4-position. This leads to compounds such as C.I. Mordant Black 3 which form stable chromium complexes. Excess diazo compound can lead to disazo acid dyes such as C.I. Acid Brown 43.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="12">Nitroso compounds can condense with α-naphthol for example, N,N-dimethyl-4-nitrosoaniline reacts to give indophenol.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="13">Halogenated derivatives of α-naphthol have minor uses as shown by the reaction of 4-chloro-1-naphthol and 4-bromo-1-naphthol with substituted isatin-α-chlorides to form blue indigoid vat dyes.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="14">Several important agrochemicals are derived from α-naphthol.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="15">1-Naphthoxyacetic acid is prepared by aqueous alkylation with chloroacetic acid. Devrinol, Stauffer's 2-(1-naphthoxy)-N,N-diethylpropionamide herbicide, is obtained by the reaction of 1-naphthol and N,N-diethyl-α-bromopropionamide in MeOH – NaOMe at reflux. Sevin is Union Carbide's insecticide based on 1-naphthyl methylcarbamate, carbaryl, which is produced from 1-naphthyl chloroformate and methylamine or by reaction of 1-naphthol with methyl isocyanate. Its main use lies in the control of earthworms and certain caterpillars. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="16">Important drugs are also derived from α-naphthol. The ester 1-naphthyl salicylate, Alphol, has been used as an antiseptic and antirheumatic, and ICI's 1-isopropylamino-3-(1-naphthoxy)-2-propanol, Inderal, is an important member of a new class of adrenergic β-blockers for the treatment of heart disease. Production of 21 involves reaction of 15 with epichlorohydrin followed by isopropylamine.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="17">Related products used as β-blockers or antiarrhythmics include nadoxolol and nadolol. Many analogues and alternative syntheses of this type of compound have been patented.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="18">Condensation of 1-naphthol with aniline at 180 °C gives N-phenyl-1-naphthylamine which is used as a rubber antioxidant.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="19">α-Naphthol is much less important than 2-naphthol as a dye intermediate. Apart from the historical interest in simple azo derivatives such as Orange I, the equilibrium with the keto form is an example of the prevalence of keto forms in many azo naphthol derivatives.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="20">Certain diazo components, for example, 1-amino-2-hydroxynaphthalene - 4 - sulfonic acid, under strongly alkaline conditions, couple with 1-naphthol in the 2-position rather than the conventional 4-position. This leads to compounds such as C.I. Mordant Black 3 which form stable chromium complexes. Excess diazo compound can lead to disazo acid dyes such as C.I. Acid Brown 43.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="21">Nitroso compounds can condense with α-naphthol for example, N,N-dimethyl-4-nitrosoaniline reacts to give indophenol.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="22">Halogenated derivatives of α-naphthol have minor uses as shown by the reaction of 4-chloro-1-naphthol and 4-bromo-1-naphthol with substituted isatin-α-chlorides to form blue indigoid vat dyes.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="23"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="24">Frischknecht R., Jungbluth N., Althaus H.-J., Doka G., Dones R., Heck T., Hellweg S., Hischier R., Nemecek T., Rebitzer G. and Spielmann M. (2007) Overview and Methodology. Final report ecoinvent v2.0 No. 1. Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, CH, retrieved from: www.ecoinvent.org.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="25"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="26">Gendorf (2000) Umwelterklärung 2000, Werk Gendorf. Werk Gendorf, Burgkirchen as pdf-File under: http://www.gendorf.de/pdf/umwelterklaerung2000.pdf</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="27"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="28">Gerald Booth: Naphthalene Derivatives. Published online: 2000. In: Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Che-mistry, Seventh Edition, 2004 Electronic Release (ed. Fiedler E., Grossmann G., Kersebohm D., Weiss G. and Witte C.). 7 th Electronic Release Edition. Wiley InterScience, New York, DOI: 10.1002/14356007.a17_009</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
